example.p:
This system of equations can be rewritten as the matrix equation

\begin{bmatrix}
1&1&0&0\\1&0&-2&0\\0&0&0&1\\0&1&0&-1
\end{bmatrix}
\colvector{(a_1-a_2)\\(b_1-b_2)\\(c_1-c_2)\\(d_1-d_2)}=\colvector{0\\0\\0\\0}

statement.p:
Suppose $\ltdefn{T}{U}{V}$ is a linear transformation and $\vect{v}\in V$.  If the preimage $\preimage{T}{\vect{v}}$ is non-empty, and $\vect{u}\in\preimage{T}{\vect{v}}$  then

\preimage{T}{\vect{v}}=
\setparts{\vect{u}+\vect{z}}{\vect{z}\in\krn{T}}
=\vect{u}+\krn{T}

proof.p:
Let $M=\setparts{\vect{u}+\vect{z}}{\vect{z}\in\krn{T}}$. First, we show that $M\subseteq\preimage{T}{\vect{v}}$. Suppose that $\vect{w}\in M$, so $\vect{w}$ has the form $\vect{w}=\vect{u}+\vect{z}$, where $\vect{z}\in\krn{T}$. Then
\lt{T}{\vect{w}}&=\lt{T}{\vect{u}+\vect{z}}\\ &=\lt{T}{\vect{u}}+\lt{T}{\vect{z}}&&\text{}\\ &=\vect{v}+\zerovector&&\vect{u}\in\preimage{T}{\vect{v}},\ \vect{z}\in\krn{T}\\ &=\vect{v}&&\text{}
which qualifies $\vect{w}$ for membership in the preimage of $\vect{v}$, $\vect{w}\in\preimage{T}{\vect{v}}$.

 We assume $T$ is injective and we need to establish that two sets are equal ().  Since the kernel is a subspace (), $\set{\zerovector}\subseteq\krn{T}$.  To establish the opposite inclusion, suppose $\vect{x}\in\krn{T}$.

\lt{T}{\vect{x}}
&=\zerovector&&\text{}\\
&=\lt{T}{\zerovector}
&&\text{}

  To establish that $T$ is injective, appeal to  and begin with the assumption that $\lt{T}{\vect{x}}=\lt{T}{\vect{y}}$.  Then

\lt{T}{\vect{x}-\vect{y}}
&=\lt{T}{\vect{x}}-\lt{T}{\vect{y}}
&&\text{}\\
&=\zerovector
&&\text{Hypothesis}

So $\vect{x}-\vect{y}\in\krn{T}$ by  and with the hypothesis that the kernel is trivial we conclude that $\vect{x}-\vect{y}=\zerovector$.  Then

\vect{y}
=\vect{y}+\zerovector
=\vect{y}+\left(\vect{x}-\vect{y}\right)
=\vect{x}

thus establishing that $T$ is injective by .

example.p:
The key is the vector
\vect{z}=\colvector{3\\4\\1\\3\\3}
which you can check is an element of $\krn{T}$ for . Choose a vector $\vect{x}$ at random, and then compute $\vect{y}=\vect{x}+\vect{z}$ (verify this computation back in ). Then
\lt{T}{\vect{y}}&=\lt{T}{\vect{x}+\vect{z}}\\ &=\lt{T}{\vect{x}}+\lt{T}{\vect{z}}&&\text{}\\ &=\lt{T}{\vect{x}}+\zerovector&&\vect{z}\in\krn{T}\\ &=\lt{T}{\vect{x}}&&\text{}

In  the kernel of  was determined to be

\spn{}
a subspace of $\complex{3}$ with dimension 1.  Since the kernel is not trivial,  tells us that $T$ is not injective.

proof.p:
Then,

\zerovector
&=\lt{T}{\vect{u}}
&&\text{}\\
&=\lt{T}{\lincombo{a}{u}{m}}
&&\text{}\\
&=a_1\lt{T}{\vect{u}_1}+a_2\lt{T}{\vect{u}_2}+a_3\lt{T}{\vect{u}_3}+\cdots+a_m\lt{T}{\vect{u}_m}
&&\text{}

That the composition is a linear transformation was established in , so we need only establish that the composition is injective.  Applying , choose $\vect{x}$, $\vect{y}$ from $U$.  Then if $\lt{\left(\compose{S}{T}\right)}{\vect{x}}=\lt{\left(\compose{S}{T}\right)}{\vect{y}}$,

&\Rightarrow&\lt{S}{\lt{T}{\vect{x}}}&=\lt{S}{\lt{T}{\vect{y}}}
&&\text{}\\
&\Rightarrow&\lt{T}{\vect{x}}&=\lt{T}{\vect{y}}
&&\text{ for $S$}\\
&\Rightarrow&\vect{x}&=\vect{y}
&&\text{ for $T$}

exercise.solution:
A linear transformation that is not injective will have a non-trivial kernel (), and this is the key to finding the desired inputs.  We need one non-trivial element of the kernel, so suppose that $\vect{z}\in\complex{4}$ is an element of the kernel,

\colvector{0\\0\\0}
=\zerovector
=\lt{T}{\vect{z}}
=\colvector{
2z_1+z_2+z_3\\
-z_1+3z_2+z_3-z_4\\
3z_1+z_2+2z_3-2z_4
}

Vector equality  leads to the homogeneous system of three equations in four variables,

2z_1+z_2+z_3&=0\\
-z_1+3z_2+z_3-z_4&=0\\
3z_1+z_2+2z_3-2z_4&=0

The coefficient matrix of this system row-reduces as

\begin{bmatrix}
 2 & 1 & 1 & 0 \\
 -1 & 3 & 1 & -1 \\
 3 & 1 & 2 & -2
\end{bmatrix}
\rref
\begin{bmatrix}
 \leading{1} & 0 & 0 & 1 \\
 0 & \leading{1} & 0 & 1 \\
 0 & 0 & \leading{1} & -3
\end{bmatrix}

From this we can find a solution (we only need one), that is an element of $\krn{T}$,

\vect{z}=\colvector{-1\\-1\\3\\1}

Now, we choose a vector $\vect{x}$ at random and set $\vect{y}=\vect{x}+\vect{z}$,

\vect{x}
&=\colvector{2\\3\\4\\-2}
&
\vect{y}&=\vect{x}+\vect{z}=
\colvector{2\\3\\4\\-2}+\colvector{-1\\-1\\3\\1}
=\colvector{1\\2\\7\\-1}

and you can check that

\lt{T}{\vect{x}}
=\colvector{11\\13\\21}
=\lt{T}{\vect{y}}

A quicker solution is to take two elements of the kernel (in this case, scalar multiples of $\vect{z}$) which both get sent to $\zerovector$ by $T$.  Quicker yet, take $\zerovector$ and $\vect{z}$ as $\vect{x}$ and $\vect{y}$, which also both get sent to $\zerovector$ by $T$.

exercise.problem:
Define the linear transformation
\ltdefn{T}{\complex{3}}{\complex{2}},\quad \lt{T}{\colvector{x_1\\x_2\\x_3}}=\colvector{2x_1-x_2+5x_3\\-4x_1+2x_2-10x_3}
Find a basis for the kernel of $T$, $\krn{T}$. Is $T$ injective?

exercise.solution:
To find the kernel, we require all $\vect{x}\in\complex{3}$ such that $\lt{T}{\vect{x}}=\zerovector$.  This condition is

\colvector{2x_1-x_2+5x_3\\-4x_1+2x_2-10x_3}=\colvector{0\\0}

This leads to a homogeneous system of two linear equations in three variables, whose coefficient matrix row-reduces to

\begin{bmatrix}
\leading{1} & -\frac{1}{2} & \frac{5}{2}\\
0 & 0 & 0
\end{bmatrix}

With two free variables  yields the basis for the null space

\set{
\colvector{-\frac{5}{2}\\0\\1},\,
\colvector{\frac{1}{2}\\1\\0}
}




With $\nullity{T}\neq 0$, $\krn{T}\neq\set{\zerovector}$, so  says $T$ is not injective.

Since $T$ is given by matrix multiplication, $\krn{T} = \nsp{A}$.  We have

\begin{bmatrix}
1 & 2 & 3 & 1\\
2 & -1 & 1 & 0\\
1 & 2 & -1 & -2 \\
1 & 3 & 2 & 1
\end{bmatrix}
&\rref
\begin{bmatrix}
\leading{1} & 0 & 0 & 0\\
0 & \leading{1} & 0 & 0\\
0 & 0 & \leading{1} & 0\\
0 & 0 & 0 & \leading{1}
\end{bmatrix}

The nullspace of $A$ is $\set{\zerovector}$, so the kernel of $T$ is also trivial:  $\krn{T} = \set{\zerovector}$.

Since $T$ is given by matrix multiplication, $\krn{T} = \nsp{A}$. We have
\begin{bmatrix} 1 & 2 & 1 & 1\\ 2 & 1 & 1 & 0\\ 1 & 2 & 1 & 2 \\ 1 & 2 & 1 & 1 \end{bmatrix} &\rref \begin{bmatrix} \leading{1} & 0 & 1/3 & 0\\ 0 & \leading{1} & 1/3 & 0\\ 0 & 0 & 0 & \leading{1}\\ 0 & 0 & 0 & 0 \end{bmatrix}
Thus, a basis for the nullspace of $A$ is $\set{\colvector{-1\\-1\\3\\0}}$, and the kernel is $\krn{T} = \spn{\spn{\colvector{-1\\-1\\3\\0}}}$. Since the kernel is nontrivial, this linear transformation is not injective.

exercise.problem:
Given that the linear transformation $\ltdefn{T}{\complex{3}}{\complex{3}}$,
$\lt{T}{\colvector{x\\y\\z}} = \colvector{2x + y\\2y + z\\x + 2z}$
is injective, show directly that
$\set{
\lt{T}{\vect{e}_1},\,
\lt{T}{\vect{e}_2},\,
\lt{T}{\vect{e}_3}
}$
is a linearly independent set.

exercise.solution:
We have

\lt{T}{\vect{e}_1} &= \colvector{2\\0\\1}
&
\lt{T}{\vect{e}_2} &= \colvector{1\\2\\0}
&
\lt{T}{\vect{e}_3} &= \colvector{0\\1\\2}

Let's put these vectors into a matrix and row reduce to test their linear independence.

\begin{bmatrix}
2 & 1 & 0\\
0 & 2 & 1\\
1 & 0 & 2
\end{bmatrix}
&\rref
\begin{bmatrix}
\leading{1} & 0 & 0\\
0 & \leading{1} & 0\\
0 & 0 & \leading{1}
\end{bmatrix}

so the set of vectors
$\set{\lt{T}{\vect{e}_1},\, \lt{T}{\vect{e}_1},\,\lt{T}{\vect{e}_1}}$
is linearly independent.

exercise.problem:
Given that the linear transformation $\ltdefn{T}{\complex{2}}{\complex{3}}$,
$\lt{T}{\colvector{x\\y}} = \colvector{x+y\\2x + y\\x + 2y}$ is injective, show directly that
$\set{
\lt{T}{\vect{e}_1},\,
\lt{T}{\vect{e}_2}
}$
is a linearly independent set.

exercise.solution:
We have $\lt{T}{\vect{e}_1} = \colvector{1\\2\\1}$ and $\lt{T}{\vect{e}_2} = \colvector{1\\1\\2}$.  Putting these into a matrix as columns and row-reducing, we have

\begin{bmatrix}
1 & 1\\
2 & 1\\
1 & 2
\end{bmatrix}
&\rref
\begin{bmatrix}
\leading{1} & 0 \\
0 & \leading{1}\\
0 & 0
\end{bmatrix}

Thus, the set of vectors $\set{\lt{T}{\vect{e}_1},\,\lt{T}{\vect{e}_2}}$ is linearly independent.

We have

\lt{T}{\vect{e}_1} &= \colvector{1\\0\\1\\1\\3}
&
\lt{T}{\vect{e}_2} &= \colvector{3\\1\\2\\0\\1}
&
\lt{T}{\vect{e}_3} &= \colvector{2\\1\\1\\1\\2}

Let's row reduce the matrix of $T$  to test linear independence.

\begin{bmatrix}
1 & 3 & 2\\
0 & 1 & 1\\
1 & 2 & 1\\
1 & 0 & 1\\
3 & 1 & 2
\end{bmatrix}
&\rref
\begin{bmatrix}
\leading{1} & 0 & 0\\
0 & \leading{1} & 0\\
0 & 0 & \leading{1} \\
0 & 0 & 0\\
0 & 0 & 0
\end{bmatrix}

so the set of vectors $\set{\lt{T}{\vect{e}_1},\,\lt{T}{\vect{e}_2},\,\lt{T}{\vect{e}_3}}$ is linearly independent.

We choose $\vect{x}$ to be any vector we like.  A particularly cocky choice would be to choose $\vect{x}=\zerovector$, but we will instead choose

\vect{x}= \begin{bmatrix} 2 & -1 \\ -1 & 4 \end{bmatrix}

Then $\lt{R}{\vect{x}}=9+9x$.  Now compute the kernel of $R$, which by <acroref type="theorem" acro="KILT" /> we expect to be nontrivial.  Setting $\lt{R}{\begin{bmatrix}a&b\\b&c\end{bmatrix}}$ equal to the zero vector, $\zerovector=0+0x$, and equating coefficients leads to a homogeneous system of equations.  Row-reducing the coefficient matrix of this system will allow us to determine the values of $a$, $b$ and $c$ that create elements of the null space of $R$,

\begin{bmatrix}
 2 & -1 & 1 \\
 1 & 1 & 2
\end{bmatrix}
\rref
\begin{bmatrix}
 \leading{1} & 0 & 1 \\
 0 & \leading{1} & 1
\end{bmatrix}

We only need a single element of the null space of this coefficient matrix, so we will not compute a precise description of the whole null space.  Instead, choose the free variable $c=2$.  Then

\vect{z}=\begin{bmatrix} -2 & -2 \\ -2 & 2\end{bmatrix}

is the corresponding element of the kernel.  We compute the desired $\vect{y}$ as

\vect{y}=\vect{x}+\vect{z}=
\begin{bmatrix} 2 & -1 \\ -1 & 4 \end{bmatrix}
+
\begin{bmatrix} -2 & -2 \\ -2 & 2\end{bmatrix}
=
\begin{bmatrix}  0 & -3 \\ -3 & 6 \end{bmatrix}

Then check that $\lt{R}{\vect{y}}=9+9x$.

We are asked to prove that $\krn{T}$ is a subset of $\krn{\compose{S}{T}}$. Employing , choose $\vect{x}\in\krn{T}$. Then we know that $\lt{T}{\vect{x}}=\zerovector$. So
\lt{\left(\compose{S}{T}\right)}{\vect{x}}&=\lt{S}{\lt{T}{\vect{x}}}&&\text{}\\ &=\lt{S}{\zerovector}&&\vect{x}\in\krn{T}\\ &=\zerovector&&\text{}
This qualifies $\vect{x}$ for membership in $\krn{\compose{S}{T}}$.

exercise.problem:
Suppose that $A$ is an $m\times n$ matrix.  Define the linear transformation $T$ by

\ltdefn{T}{\complex{n}}{\complex{m}},\quad \lt{T}{\vect{x}}=A\vect{x}

Prove that the kernel of $T$ equals the null space of $A$, $\krn{T}=\nsp{A}$.

exercise.solution:
This is an equality of sets, so we want to establish two subset conditions ().


First, show $\nsp{A}\subseteq\krn{T}$.  Choose $\vect{x}\in\nsp{A}$.  Check to see if $\vect{x}\in\krn{T}$,

\lt{T}{\vect{x}}
&=A\vect{x}&&\text{Definition of $T$}\\
&=\zerovector&&\text{$\vect{x}\in\nsp{A}$}

So by , $\vect{x}\in\krn{T}$ and thus $\nsp{A}\subseteq\krn{T}$.


Now, show $\krn{T}\subseteq\nsp{A}$.  Choose $\vect{x}\in\krn{T}$.  Check to see if $\vect{x}\in\nsp{A}$,

A\vect{x}
&=\lt{T}{\vect{x}}&&\text{Definition of $T$}\\
&=\zerovector&&\text{$\vect{x}\in\krn{T}$}

So by , $\vect{x}\in\nsp{A}$ and thus $\krn{T}\subseteq\nsp{A}$.
